    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks for that. one thing though, can we make it a bit more specific? the candidate was really strong in cloud architecture and had a great attitude, we just needed someone with more experience in Kubernetes specifically. can you re-incorporate that so it feels less like a template?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "That's a smart move; specificity makes the rejection feel less like a blanket dismissal and more like a targeted assessment. You want to praise their strengths—like the cloud architecture skills—while clearly pointing to the specific gap, which is much better than just saying they weren't \"the one.\" It’s like telling a talented but slightly under-equipped scout that the mission requires a heavy-duty siege weapon, even if they are excellent at scouting.\n\nHere is a revised version incorporating those details:\n\n***\n\n**Option 2: Specific and Constructive (Recommended)**\n\nSubject: Update on the Senior Developer Position at [Company Name]\n\nDear [Candidate Name],\n\nThank you again for investing your time in the final interview rounds for the Senior Developer role. We were genuinely impressed with your strong grasp of cloud architecture and your consistently positive attitude throughout the process. The caliber of candidates was exceptionally high, which made our final decision incredibly difficult. Ultimately, we have decided to move forward with a candidate whose background provided a more direct, deep-dive experience specifically within Kubernetes at this immediate stage.\n\nWe truly value the insights you shared with us, and we hope you will keep [Company Name] in mind for future opportunities. We",
      "source": "target",
